      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one keep their house and still get SNAP benefits?",
          "answer": "Yes. Your loved one's primary home doesn't count toward asset limits, regardless of value. They can also keep one vehicle and reasonable personal belongings without affecting SNAP eligibility."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one's income is slightly over the limit but they have high medical bills?",
          "answer": "Even if your loved one's gross income is above the standard limit, they may still qualify. Seniors (60+) can deduct verified out-of-pocket medical expenses that exceed $35/month from their income. These deductions lower their countable income, often bringing them under the limit to qualify for benefits. Always apply; many seniors are surprised to find they are eligible after these deductions are applied."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SNAP on behalf of my elderly loved one?",
          "answer": "Yes, adult children can apply as authorized representatives if their loved one gives permission. You'll need to complete an authorized representative form and may need to attend the eligibility interview with or instead of your loved one."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much will my loved one actually receive each month?",
          "answer": "It depends on net income after deductions. For example, a single senior with $1,500/month income and $200 in medical expenses might receive around $150/month. Use the COMPASS calculator for a personalized estimate before applying."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one use SNAP benefits to buy groceries online?",
          "answer": "Yes. Pennsylvania SNAP recipients can use their EBT card for online grocery orders from Amazon, Walmart, and other approved retailers. Delivery fees aren't covered by SNAP, but the groceries are."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one lives with family but buys their own food?",
          "answer": "Only people who buy and prepare food together count as one SNAP household. If your loved one shops and cooks separately, they apply as a one-person household even if they live with relatives."
        },
        {
          "question": "How often does my loved one need to renew SNAP benefits?",
          "answer": "Seniors often receive a longer certification period—typically 24 or 36 months—making it easier to maintain benefits without frequent paperwork. You will receive renewal notices in the mail with clear instructions on when to recertify. Keep an eye on your mail, as missing these notices can cause a gap in coverage."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one get SNAP if they're already receiving Medicaid or Medicare?",
          "answer": "Yes. SNAP is a separate program from health insurance. Many seniors receive SNAP, Medicaid, Medicare, and other benefits simultaneously. Being on one program doesn't disqualify you from others."
        }
      ],
